# Paperboard — GitHub Copilot Coding Agent Instructions

Integrate `atv-paperboard` into your Copilot Coding Agent workflow to auto-render
structured outputs as self-contained HTML artifacts governed by a `DESIGN.md`.

## When to invoke `paperboard render`

Invoke after any tool writes a file that matches **one or more** of these patterns:

| Trigger | Examples |
|---------|---------|
| Status dashboards | Build status table, CI results matrix, test pass/fail grid |
| Comparison tables | Model benchmarks, A/B experiment results, feature comparisons |
| Output viewers | LLM evaluation sheets, structured JSON summaries, scoring rubrics |
| Data tables with ≥2 numeric columns | Performance metrics, cost breakdowns, load test results |
| Markdown files with `status`/`score`/`result`/`count` column headers | Any agent-generated report |

## How to invoke

```bash
paperboard render --input <path-to-file> [--tier atv|pico|daisy] [--no-open]
```

Pass `--no-open` in CI / headless environments.

## Tier policy

Default tier is **`atv`** for dashboards and reports — it is the dark, designed-document
tier and is the right choice for nearly all agent-generated artifacts. Use **`pico`**
(or `daisy`) only when the target audience explicitly wants a light, framework-styled
document. When in doubt, omit `--tier` and let the `atv` default apply.

## After rendering

Run `paperboard gallery` to refresh the local artifact index at `paperboard-artifacts/gallery.html`.

## Do NOT invoke for

- Pure prose documentation (README, CHANGELOG, design docs)
- Files in `.github/`, `docs/`, or `node_modules/`
- Files the render step itself produces (self-recursion guard)

## Harness detection

`paperboard` auto-detects the harness. No configuration needed when running under
GitHub Copilot Coding Agent (resolves to `copilot` harness, writes to `paperboard-artifacts/`).

## Design authority

When generating or modifying `.DESIGN.md` files, follow the binding doctrine
in `core/designs/DESIGN-AUTHORITY.md`. The doctrine is derived from
[pbakaus/impeccable](https://github.com/pbakaus/impeccable) (Apache 2.0,
pinned at commit `4af581e23f17d112d8f9d6b7a5b7ff37823494e1`).

Absolute bans (non-negotiable):

- Glassmorphism (`backdrop-filter: blur`, frosted overlays)
- Gradient text (`-webkit-background-clip: text` with a gradient fill)
- Side-stripe borders (a colored bar on one edge of a card without semantic meaning)
- Nested card-in-card patterns
- Generic AI emoji clichés used decoratively (✨🚀⚡🎯…)

The seven reference dimensions (typography, color-and-contrast, spatial-design,
motion-design, interaction-design, responsive-design, ux-writing) are vendored
at `core/designs/impeccable-context/` for offline reference.

Paperboard adopts impeccable's *methodology* (how design tokens are authored
and enforced), not its *aesthetic* (warm Cormorant Garamond editorial palette).
Paperboard retains its own cold-dark-technical identity.
